-- 
Topix Falls for a Second Day as Nippon Yusen Leads Shipping Lines Lower

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a
-- 
2011-03-08T07:38:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/japan-s-stocks-gain-led-by-oil-companies-on-libya-violence-hitachi-rises.html
The Topix dropped for a second day
after Nippon Yusen K.K. said it may slow its  container ships  to
save fuel amid higher  oil prices .  Hitachi Ltd. (6501)  advanced after it
agreed to sell its hard disk-drive business.  Shipping companies led declines after Nippon Yusen, Japan’s
largest fleet operator by sales, said it may reduce vessel
speeds by 10 percent in order to cut costs. Hitachi, which makes
everything from home appliances to nuclear reactors, gained 1.8
percent after agreeing to sell its disk-drive unit to Western
Digital Corp. Terumo, Japan’s No. 1 medical-device maker,
climbed 3.2 percent after saying it will buy a unit of Gambro AB
that makes blood transfusion equipment.  The Topix index fell 0.3 percent to 939.16 as of the 3 p.m.
close in Tokyo after earlier advancing as much as 0.4 percent.
The  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average rose 0.2 percent to 10,525.19
following a 1.8 percent slide yesterday amid intensified
fighting in  Libya  and a surge in oil prices that heightening
concern higher fuel costs will impede the economic recovery.  “The market is scatter-shot,” said Koichi Kurose, chief
strategist in Tokyo at Resona Bank Ltd., which oversees the
equivalent of $57 billion in assets. “When there’s a general
feeling of anxiety or a sense that you’ve got to be on guard
about political events or other surprises, investors make short-
term trades.”  Qaddafi’s Offer  Oil prices have risen about 25 percent since protesters
began calling for the ouster of leader  Muammar Qaddafi  on Feb.
16. Crude for April delivery fell today for the first time in
three days, dropping as much as 97 cents to $104.47 a barrel in
electronic trading on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  after al-
Jazeera reported Qaddafi offered to relinquish power. The
proposal was rejected by a rebel council, the TV channel said.  Shipping lines had the biggest drop among the Topix’s 33
industry groups after Nippon Yusen said it may slow its fleet.
The company lost 2.5 percent to 346 yen, while Mitsui O.S.K.
Lines Ltd., Japan’s second largest shipping line, slid 1.5
percent to 532 yen, while No. 3 Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd.
declined 2.8 percent to 346 yen.  Banks were the heaviest drag on the Topix after  Bank of
Japan  figures showed that lending declined last month more than
economists expected. Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group Inc., the
country’s biggest publicly traded bank, dropped 0.9 percent to
443 yen. Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group Inc., Japan’s second-
largest lender, slid 1.4 percent to 2,988 yen.  Hitachi, Terumo Deals  The Topix has risen 4.5 percent this year, compared with
gains of 4.2 percent by the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and 1.8
percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Shares in the Topix were
valued at 15.8 times estimated earnings on average, compared
with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.2 times for the Stoxx 600.  Hitachi advanced 1.8 percent to 514 yen, the most active
stock by value in Japan, after Western Digital agreed to buy
Hitachi Global Storage Technologies, a wholly-owned Hitachi unit,
for about $4.3 billion.  Terumo jumped 3.2 percent to 4,640 yen after agreeing to
purchase Gambro’s CaridianBCT unit for $2.63 billion, creating
the world’s biggest maker of blood-transfusion equipment.  Shinko Electric Industries Co., a maker of semiconductor
packages, sank 3.9 percent to 938 yen after Barclays Plc cut its
rating on the stock to “underweight” from “equal-weight.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Norie Kuboyama in Tokyo at 
 nkuboyama@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
